WEBVTT

00:09.727 --> 00:12.560
Is it me or is the foam
a tad dense today?

00:12.727 --> 00:15.446
Like a dreary fog on a Scottish moor.

00:15.607 --> 00:18.167
Rather than accent, it overwhelms.

00:18.367 --> 00:20.483
Rather than flirt, it assaults.

00:20.687 --> 00:24.077
Rather than watching the ball game,
I have to listen to this.

00:25.607 --> 00:26.960
ROZ: Hey, you guys.
- Hey, Roz.

00:27.127 --> 00:28.276
- Like to join us?
- Oh, yes.

00:28.447 --> 00:32.042
Frasier, listen, don't forget your staff
meeting tomorrow. It starts at...

00:34.087 --> 00:37.921
Well, I certainly hope his tailor can fix
the holes you just burnt in his jacket.

00:38.367 --> 00:40.835
They're not in his jacket.

00:41.367 --> 00:43.039
- It starts tomorrow at 10.
- Thank you.

00:43.207 --> 00:44.686
Hey, Marty, what are
you doing here?

00:44.847 --> 00:47.122
They're dragging me out
to buy some new clothes.

00:47.287 --> 00:49.642
We're taking him to Rudolfo's
once-a-year sale.

00:49.847 --> 00:51.644
It's 50 percent off.
The alterations are free.

00:51.847 --> 00:53.883
Big deal. Butz Clothiers,
they do that every day.

00:54.047 --> 00:58.199
Yes, not to mention the convenience
of getting your pizza right next door.

00:58.407 --> 01:00.318
These guys think I have
bad taste in clothes.

01:00.527 --> 01:01.676
I like the way you dress.

01:01.887 --> 01:03.843
That's what's called the "clincher."
Shall we go?

01:05.126 --> 01:08.676
All right. Well, I'll just hit the head,
and we can get it over with.

01:08.847 --> 01:10.439
Dad, you could show
more enthusiasm.

01:10.607 --> 01:11.596
- Yeah.
MARTIN: Okay.

01:11.847 --> 01:14.759
Gee, I can't wait to hit the head,
and we can get it all over with!

01:19.287 --> 01:21.118
Are you finished undressing him
with your eyes?

01:21.327 --> 01:22.999
Please. I'm already
looking for my stockings

01:23.167 --> 01:25.635
and trying to remember
where I parked my car.

01:26.847 --> 01:28.758
I would have thought that gentleman
over there

01:28.927 --> 01:30.679
in the flannel shirt
would be more your type.

01:30.847 --> 01:33.236
Him? Not a chance.

01:33.527 --> 01:35.165
See the way he's slurping
his orange juice?

01:35.327 --> 01:37.124
Sloppy kisser.

01:37.447 --> 01:39.677
Now, you can tell right away
the guy is no good in bed.

01:39.847 --> 01:41.360
He's so cautious.

01:41.567 --> 01:44.240
Look at the way he's blowing
on his coffee.

01:51.167 --> 01:54.921
I wasn't trying to cool it,
I was simply blowing a foam hole.

01:55.487 --> 01:57.523
You don't even wrinkle
the sheets, do you?

01:58.807 --> 02:01.879
Niles, that man across the street
at the newsstand.

02:02.047 --> 02:03.366
Is that who I think it is?

02:03.567 --> 02:04.841
He does look familiar.

02:05.047 --> 02:06.924
- It's T.H. Houghton.
- No!

02:07.087 --> 02:10.044
<i>Just think back to the picture on the
dust cover of his Time Flies Tomorrow.</i>

02:10.207 --> 02:12.357
<i>- A little older, greyer...
- Yeah, Time Flies Tomorrow.</i>

02:12.527 --> 02:13.562
I read that in high school.

02:13.727 --> 02:15.365
- What else did he write?
FRASIER: Nothing.

02:15.567 --> 02:18.240
That's the crux of his legend.
The man published one masterpiece,

02:18.407 --> 02:20.875
and in the 30 years since,
he's become a virtual recluse.

02:21.047 --> 02:24.164
- Oh, my God. It is T.H. Houghton.
- Yes.

02:24.367 --> 02:27.165
We're a stone's throw away
from one of the giants of literature.

02:27.367 --> 02:28.880
Not the way you throw.

02:30.007 --> 02:31.440
Oh, Niles, this is incredible.

02:31.607 --> 02:34.565
My God, the man's entire life is
shrouded in mystery, yet there he is.

02:34.727 --> 02:35.876
I've always idolized him.

02:36.047 --> 02:37.685
What I wouldn't give
to meet that man.

02:37.887 --> 02:39.320
Why don't you go introduce yourself.

02:39.527 --> 02:41.677
Oh, I can't just walk up
to a god like that.

02:41.887 --> 02:43.479
Well, then find a subtler way.

02:43.687 --> 02:46.247
In your vernacular, that would
be what? To slingshot your panties

02:46.407 --> 02:47.556
across the street?

02:47.927 --> 02:51.078
- Foam blower.
- All right, all right, you two.

02:52.127 --> 02:53.446
Niles, she happens to be right.

02:53.847 --> 02:56.236
How often do you get an opportunity
like this? Let's go.

02:56.447 --> 02:58.005
All right.

02:58.167 --> 02:59.964
- Come on, we're going.
- Why? What's the rush?

03:00.127 --> 03:01.879
- T. H. Houghton is across the street.
- Who?

03:02.087 --> 03:05.159
- Come on, let's... Let's go!
MARTIN: Hey, guy with a cane here!

03:12.887 --> 03:15.196
Niles, I thought you said you saw
Houghton come in here.

03:15.367 --> 03:18.200
Well, I'm sorry if my tracking skills
aren't up to your standard.

03:18.407 --> 03:19.840
Instead of asking for a baby brother,

03:20.007 --> 03:22.601
you should have asked for a
German short-haired pointer.

03:23.007 --> 03:23.996
I did.

03:25.727 --> 03:27.285
Well, I'm sorry.

03:27.447 --> 03:28.926
He must still be out on the street.

03:29.127 --> 03:30.765
I'm parking it.
They got the Mariners on.

03:30.927 --> 03:33.316
- Please, we can't waste time.
- Let him be. He's deadweight.

03:33.527 --> 03:34.516
FRASIER:
Right.

03:38.127 --> 03:41.437
- What's the score?
- Four to three, Mariners.

03:42.207 --> 03:43.526
BOTH:
Aw!

03:44.167 --> 03:47.159
- How could he miss the cut-off man?
- That man makes 7 million a year.

03:47.327 --> 03:48.646
- It's crazy.
- Yeah.

03:48.807 --> 03:52.641
See him scratching his butt?
That's about 5 grand right there.

03:53.127 --> 03:55.687
- Let me have a Ballantine's.
- Yeah, make it two.

03:56.007 --> 03:57.725
BOTH:
Aw!

04:00.447 --> 04:02.483
So that's your favourite character?

04:02.647 --> 04:03.796
- Really?
- Yeah.

04:04.007 --> 04:07.238
Yeah, I really like him. The kind of guy
you can just sit and have a beer with.

04:07.447 --> 04:11.406
Well, I could see you saying that
about Hoss, but Little Joe?

04:12.287 --> 04:14.926
<i>That's the great thing about Bonanza.
Something for everyone.</i>

04:16.966 --> 04:19.083
Well, thank you, Mr False Alarm.

04:19.247 --> 04:21.158
"Oh, look, there he is,
over at the yogurt store!

04:21.327 --> 04:23.318
Oh, look, there he is,
in the futon store!

04:23.487 --> 04:25.955
Oh, look, there he is with Dad!"

04:26.927 --> 04:28.519
NILES:
And now he's leaving.

04:28.727 --> 04:30.445
I must tell him what an impact
his book has made.

04:30.607 --> 04:32.120
Aren't you afraid
it'll sound unoriginal?

04:32.287 --> 04:33.481
- Why?
- I'm gonna say it first.

04:33.647 --> 04:35.319
MAN: Excuse me, Mr Houghton?
- Yeah?

04:35.527 --> 04:39.156
- I just wanted to tell you that...
- My book changed your life. Swell.

04:39.607 --> 04:42.075
- No, no, but I...
- It changed mine too. Look, I'm sorry.

04:42.287 --> 04:45.006
I don't like to discuss my work.

04:47.167 --> 04:48.919
Well, that was humiliating.

04:49.087 --> 04:50.805
I've never felt so rejected in my life.

04:51.007 --> 04:52.281
Now, now, don't take it so hard.

04:52.447 --> 04:53.846
Who was to know
he was so sensitive?

04:54.047 --> 04:57.517
- Aren't you Dr Crane from the radio?
- Not now, haven't got the time, sorry.

04:58.847 --> 05:00.678
Do you realize who you were
just talking to?

05:00.847 --> 05:02.519
- That was T. H. Houghton.
- Yeah, I know.

05:02.727 --> 05:04.797
Well, well, well,
what did you two talk about?

05:04.967 --> 05:07.242
- Oh, I don't know. This and that.
FRASIER: Dad,

05:07.447 --> 05:09.483
virtually nothing is known
about this man.

05:09.647 --> 05:11.080
Can't you give us
something specific?

05:11.287 --> 05:15.485
Well, it was just guy stuff, you know.
Baseball, TV shows, old war stories...

05:15.687 --> 05:17.086
- He told war stories?
- No, I did.

05:17.247 --> 05:19.807
You know, about the time I made
the stew and the platoon got sick.

05:19.967 --> 05:21.605
Dad, how could you?

05:21.807 --> 05:23.320
What? He liked it.

05:23.487 --> 05:25.717
He's a nice guy. I think maybe
I'll buy one of his books.

05:25.927 --> 05:29.158
Not books, Dad. Book.

05:29.327 --> 05:30.316
Book.

05:30.527 --> 05:33.121
He wrote one book
and never wrote again.

05:33.327 --> 05:35.966
If only we'd arrived ten minutes earlier,
we could've talked to him.

05:36.167 --> 05:38.362
We could have explored
that mammoth intellect.

05:38.567 --> 05:42.276
Can you imagine the torture the man's
endured, to peak at such an early age?

05:42.447 --> 05:45.120
Oh, my God, Frasier, look.
It's a doodle!

05:45.287 --> 05:46.800
Not just any doodle,
a Houghton doodle.

05:47.007 --> 05:47.996
- It's mine!
- No, mine!

05:48.167 --> 05:49.680
- It's mine.
- Dad, what do you care?

05:49.887 --> 05:50.922
No, I mean I drew it.

05:54.367 --> 05:55.959
That's very touching. This is for you.

05:56.167 --> 05:57.441
Bye-bye.

05:59.447 --> 06:01.403
I don't know when I've enjoyed
an exhibit more.

06:01.567 --> 06:05.082
The artist's choice to make that a
monochrome was a stroke of genius.

06:05.287 --> 06:07.323
- It conveyed such despair.
FRASIER: Yes.

06:07.527 --> 06:10.246
It was so refreshing
to see a sad peach.

06:11.127 --> 06:12.401
How about that curator?

06:12.607 --> 06:14.006
She was kind of a peach herself.

06:14.567 --> 06:16.876
- No cubism there, I don't think.
- No, certainly not.

06:18.407 --> 06:20.762
MARTIN: Hey, boys.
BOTH: Oh, hi, Dad.

06:21.247 --> 06:23.283
Oh, Ted. Ted, I'd like you
to meet my sons.

06:23.447 --> 06:25.324
This is Frasier and Niles.
They're big fans.

06:25.487 --> 06:27.205
- Hi, guys.
FRASIER: Mr Houghton...

06:27.367 --> 06:28.766
We...

06:29.407 --> 06:31.284
Words can't express...

06:31.487 --> 06:33.478
I guess not.

06:34.767 --> 06:36.644
Nice meeting you fellas.

06:37.447 --> 06:41.235
Oh, my God, we missed him again!

06:41.447 --> 06:42.846
- What's going on?
- That's odd.

06:43.047 --> 06:44.878
So where are you two going?

06:46.047 --> 06:48.800
Well, Ted's taking me out to this
bratwurst place he knows.

06:49.007 --> 06:51.760
Bratwurst? Yummy.
My God, that's our favourite.

06:52.247 --> 06:53.726
Nice meeting you.

06:56.607 --> 06:59.075
- What's wrong with this thing?
NILES: Well, it could be broken.

06:59.287 --> 07:01.403
If you came in to the apartment,
we'll call the front...

07:01.567 --> 07:05.162
No! I'm sure it'll work this time.

07:10.127 --> 07:11.924
What the hell was he doing here?

07:13.287 --> 07:15.482
We might know if you hadn't
spent an hour

07:15.847 --> 07:18.520
pondering the despair of the peach.

07:18.847 --> 07:20.166
From the man who spent 30 minutes

07:20.327 --> 07:23.046
<i>looking at
Woman with a Rectangular Head.</i>

07:23.247 --> 07:25.636
Oh, was Mrs Foster
in the lobby again?

07:26.247 --> 07:27.362
No, Daphne.

07:27.567 --> 07:28.716
Could you explain to me

07:28.887 --> 07:31.560
just how T. H. Houghton
ended up in my apartment?

07:31.727 --> 07:33.718
Well, he's only in town
for a couple of days,

07:33.887 --> 07:35.525
and he doesn't know
too many people,

07:35.687 --> 07:37.803
so he looked your father up,
gave him a ring,

07:37.967 --> 07:40.925
and Mr Crane invited him over
to watch the Mariners game.

07:41.927 --> 07:43.599
- He was here all afternoon?
DAPHNE: Yes.

07:43.807 --> 07:45.684
Oh, it's a shame you
couldn't be here,

07:45.847 --> 07:48.759
because he told
the most fascinating stories.

07:48.927 --> 07:52.237
And, of course, he and your father
are getting on like old chums.

07:52.447 --> 07:54.677
But the sweetest thing
was how he took to Eddie.

07:58.167 --> 07:59.998
He... He spent time with Eddie?

08:00.207 --> 08:01.606
Fed him his afternoon biscuit.

08:01.807 --> 08:04.037
FRASIER: Will the madness never end!
NILES: Oh, now, now.

08:04.207 --> 08:06.960
Let's not give up hope. Maybe
Dad'll bring him back after dinner.

08:07.127 --> 08:09.038
Oh, well, I doubt it.

08:09.207 --> 08:12.119
They'll probably run into J.D. Salinger
and Salman Rushdie

08:12.287 --> 08:14.164
and go out for margaritas.

08:15.687 --> 08:18.360
I tell you, Niles, these near misses,
they're just excruciating.

08:18.567 --> 08:19.556
[DAPHNE LAUGHING]

08:19.727 --> 08:23.003
DAPHNE: There you go,
Mr Houghton. You're welcome.

08:24.367 --> 08:26.517
- Was that him?
- Yes, he forgot his coat.

08:26.727 --> 08:28.285
FRASIER:
Make way, Daphne!

08:32.246 --> 08:34.885
We missed him again.

08:38.447 --> 08:42.645
Don't you dare gloat,
you miserable little biscuit whore.

