08:52.527 --> 08:54.006
[BARKING]

08:54.167 --> 08:55.759
Thanks, Eddie.

09:08.047 --> 09:10.038
- Afternoon, Daphne.
- Hello.

09:10.207 --> 09:11.720
Good dog.

09:13.927 --> 09:16.805
Oh, Dr Crane,
it's a good thing you're home.

09:16.967 --> 09:20.516
Mr Houghton's dropping by to pick up
your father for the Mariners game.

09:20.727 --> 09:24.163
- Are you serious? He's coming back?
- Yes, any minute. It's a double-header.

09:25.367 --> 09:27.722
- They play two games.
- Oh, right.

09:29.807 --> 09:31.923
But this is... This is incredibly
good fortune for me.

09:32.127 --> 09:35.199
I'll finally get to spend some time alone
with the man, even for a few minutes.

09:35.367 --> 09:36.561
[DOORBELL RINGS]

09:37.367 --> 09:39.198
Daphne, be a dear
and stall Dad, will you.

09:39.367 --> 09:42.245
If he gives you any trouble,
just hide his cane.

09:43.007 --> 09:44.235
Niles!

09:44.407 --> 09:46.159
What fortuitous timing.

09:46.367 --> 09:47.766
The wine shop called a moment ago.

09:47.927 --> 09:50.316
They're down to their last cases
of the '82 Chambolle-Musigny.

09:50.487 --> 09:52.682
Why don't you dash down
before somebody snaps it all up.

09:52.887 --> 09:54.798
Bless you, Frasier. Hold it.

09:58.687 --> 10:01.838
You know very well that in 1982,
there was a drought in Bourgogne.

10:04.687 --> 10:06.996
The locals dubbed it
the "Year of the Raisin."

10:10.287 --> 10:13.518
And that wine was never sold
by the case, only by the bottle.

10:14.807 --> 10:16.923
T. H. Houghton is here, isn't he?

10:18.287 --> 10:19.879
- No.
- Fine.

10:20.047 --> 10:23.198
Then you won't mind if I just
hang around for a while.

10:23.367 --> 10:25.198
Oh, all right. He's on his way.

10:25.367 --> 10:27.278
He and Dad are going
to a baseball game.

10:27.447 --> 10:28.562
It's a double-header.

10:29.607 --> 10:31.438
They play two games.

10:34.047 --> 10:35.036
Oh, hi, Niles.

10:35.207 --> 10:38.279
Oh, Dad, so I hear that
Mr Houghton is on his way over.

10:38.487 --> 10:39.920
Maybe we could all have lunch.

10:40.127 --> 10:42.561
- That's a splendid idea.
- No, the game starts in 45 minutes.

10:42.727 --> 10:44.558
Perhaps you could come by
after for a drink.

10:44.727 --> 10:46.638
No, sorry, that won't work either.

10:46.847 --> 10:49.600
He's gotta go to his publisher's,
drop off his new book.

10:51.127 --> 10:52.116
Houghton has a new book?

10:52.327 --> 10:54.318
I've lost the feeling in my legs.

10:59.247 --> 11:02.125
Well, did he say anything about it?
I mean, the characters, the setting?

11:02.327 --> 11:04.921
- No, he just said it was a book.
- Dad.

11:05.087 --> 11:06.202
You have to skip the game.

11:06.367 --> 11:07.516
It's not just for our benefit.

11:07.687 --> 11:10.724
After all this baseball, the man must
be starved for intellectual stimulation.

11:10.927 --> 11:11.962
I know what you're saying.

11:12.127 --> 11:14.357
That someone like that would
prefer to spend time with you

11:14.527 --> 11:16.245
instead of some dumbbell like me.

11:16.447 --> 11:18.756
Dad, you're not dumb.
You missed the point entirely.

11:19.247 --> 11:21.442
Let's just say, for example,
you came home one afternoon

11:21.607 --> 11:23.643
and I was sitting here
discussing literature with,

11:23.807 --> 11:25.604
I don't know, give me the name
of a player.

11:25.927 --> 11:28.885
- Darryl Strawberry.
- No, a real one!

11:29.647 --> 11:31.603
Frasier, the problem is
you push too hard.

11:31.767 --> 11:34.406
We just talk sports,
have a few laughs. That's all.

11:34.567 --> 11:35.556
[DOORBELL RINGING]

11:35.727 --> 11:37.558
You know,
I never ask him about his work.

11:37.727 --> 11:39.843
That's probably why he told me
about the book.

11:43.727 --> 11:45.797
- Mr Houghton, hello.
- Hi, how you doing?

11:46.007 --> 11:48.202
- Hey, Ted, come on in.
HOUGHTON: Fine.

11:48.367 --> 11:50.642
FRASIER: So you two boys are
off to the baseball game, huh?

11:51.127 --> 11:52.242
Double-header.

11:52.447 --> 11:54.005
That's two games.

11:56.527 --> 11:57.880
Yeah.

11:58.767 --> 12:00.519
Little-known fact about baseball.

12:00.847 --> 12:05.079
The owner of the Boston Red Sox sold
Babe Ruth to the New York Yankees

12:05.247 --> 12:08.603
<i>to finance a Broadway musical,
No, No, Nanette.</i>

12:11.647 --> 12:14.400
- You ready, Marty?
- Let's go.

12:15.087 --> 12:17.043
Well, I really enjoyed chatting
with you.

12:17.207 --> 12:21.086
If you'd drop back by after the game,
we could pick up where we left off.

12:21.807 --> 12:24.241
<i>No, No, Nanette?</i>

12:26.527 --> 12:28.404
NILES: I'm sorry,
there were exactly two things

12:28.567 --> 12:30.762
I could possibly add
to a baseball conversation.

12:30.927 --> 12:32.406
That and...

12:32.607 --> 12:34.279
No, just the one.

12:38.407 --> 12:40.443
- Frasier?
- Yes.

12:40.767 --> 12:43.804
Have you noticed how Houghton carries
a satchel with him wherever he goes?

12:44.007 --> 12:46.680
Well, actually,
as a matter of fact, I have, yes.

12:46.887 --> 12:49.447
Didn't Dad mention that Houghton
was on his way to his publisher's

12:49.607 --> 12:51.643
after the game
with a new manuscript?

12:51.847 --> 12:52.836
Yes.

12:53.047 --> 12:56.323
Wouldn't that be the very same satchel
which is now resting under my head?

12:57.607 --> 12:59.438
Oh, my God!

13:00.287 --> 13:02.118
- Wait!
- Should we?

13:02.847 --> 13:03.996
We shouldn't.

13:04.207 --> 13:06.323
- Could we live with ourselves if we did?
- Could we live with ourselves

13:06.487 --> 13:08.079
- if we didn't?
- Could we live either way?

13:08.287 --> 13:09.879
Oh, stop it, Niles!

13:10.087 --> 13:11.725
Oh, who are we kidding? All right.

13:11.927 --> 13:13.918
Careful, careful, careful.

13:25.927 --> 13:30.398
<i>"The Chameleon's Song
by T. H. Houghton."</i>

13:32.087 --> 13:33.839
These are handwritten corrections.

13:34.047 --> 13:36.686
Frasier, this is his
original manuscript.

13:36.887 --> 13:39.321
Shame on you!

13:40.567 --> 13:43.718
Going through someone else's
personal property.

13:43.927 --> 13:45.838
Well, it's just plain wrong.

13:46.047 --> 13:47.799
And I know your father
wouldn't approve.

13:48.007 --> 13:50.441
Of course, I wouldn't be here
to tell him if I had the day off.

13:50.647 --> 13:52.478
- Fine, go.
- Oh, great.

13:56.527 --> 14:00.042
Of course, having a day off
is pretty meaningless

14:00.207 --> 14:01.925
when you have no money to,
you know,

14:02.127 --> 14:05.119
maybe go to lunch
or do some shopping.

14:05.487 --> 14:09.162
Perhaps take in a show. Oh, thanks.

14:11.687 --> 14:14.520
- All right, Niles, shall we?
- Not yet.

14:14.687 --> 14:16.962
- The atmosphere has to be perfect.
- Good point, yes.

14:17.127 --> 14:19.197
Let's begin with the lighting.

14:19.367 --> 14:21.323
All right, just say when.

14:22.567 --> 14:24.159
Warmer.

14:24.887 --> 14:26.161
Warmer.

14:27.207 --> 14:28.765
A little cooler.

14:29.247 --> 14:30.760
A touch warmer.

14:30.967 --> 14:32.559
A hair back.

14:32.887 --> 14:35.606
No, no, just...
No, a hair the other way.

14:35.807 --> 14:38.844
No, a touch warmer.

14:40.287 --> 14:41.686
- Perfect.
- Good.

14:45.647 --> 14:49.117
NILES: Excellent, excellent. What wine
would most enhance the experience?

14:49.287 --> 14:51.721
No, Niles.
Wine might dull our faculties.

14:51.887 --> 14:56.597
Perhaps instead a slow-sipping cordial
would be the proper garnish.

14:56.807 --> 14:58.763
- Sherry.
- Armagnac.

14:59.327 --> 15:02.125
Oh, well, see?
That's why you're the older brother.

15:11.207 --> 15:13.038
[SIGHS]

15:13.207 --> 15:16.404
- What is it?
- I don't think you're there yet.

15:19.487 --> 15:20.556
[SIGHS]

15:34.767 --> 15:36.086
[SIGHS]

15:40.087 --> 15:41.486
[SIGHS]

15:44.127 --> 15:45.355
Well, it's a masterpiece.

15:45.527 --> 15:46.516
[BARKS]

15:46.687 --> 15:48.245
Eddie.

15:48.447 --> 15:50.085
I never thought I'd utter these words,

15:50.247 --> 15:53.478
<i>but it actually surpasses
Time Flies Tomorrow.</i>

15:53.687 --> 15:54.881
[BARKING]

15:55.047 --> 15:56.639
Eddie, please!

15:57.047 --> 15:59.117
We're trying to savour the moment.

16:10.727 --> 16:12.604
How was the game?

16:14.247 --> 16:15.362
Is that my manuscript?

16:15.527 --> 16:16.801
What the hell's going on?

16:17.007 --> 16:18.486
HOUGHTON:
You went through my bag?

16:18.687 --> 16:21.645
- That's my personal property.
- I don't believe you two.

16:22.647 --> 16:26.322
Mr Houghton, we...
We are terribly, terribly sorry.

16:26.487 --> 16:28.239
The temptation to read it
was just too great.

16:28.407 --> 16:30.045
Oh, what's that supposed to mean?

16:30.207 --> 16:32.357
You're grown men,
at least I thought you were.

16:32.527 --> 16:34.643
You had no right to touch that.

16:34.807 --> 16:37.162
Ted, I'm sorry.
I'm just so ashamed.

16:37.327 --> 16:39.158
- Now, it's all right.
- No, it's not all right.

16:39.327 --> 16:41.079
No, no, it's okay, really.

16:41.247 --> 16:43.602
Somebody had to read it first.

16:44.447 --> 16:47.245
So, what did you think?

16:48.007 --> 16:50.043
- Of the book?
- No, of my typing.

16:50.207 --> 16:51.640
Yes, of course, the book.

16:56.327 --> 16:57.396
It was great.

16:58.807 --> 17:00.035
Wow.

17:01.807 --> 17:04.958
Well, at least you liked it.
I'm gonna have to be running.

17:05.166 --> 17:06.839
Are you sure?
I was gonna make some coffee.

17:07.047 --> 17:09.083
No, no, I got an appointment.
Can I use the?

17:09.287 --> 17:11.039
- It's right here.
HOUGHTON: Okay.

17:13.767 --> 17:15.439
Boy, I've had it with you guys.

17:15.646 --> 17:17.478
If you were Hoss and Little Joe,

17:17.646 --> 17:22.323
Ben Cartwright would kick your sorry
butts right off the Ponderosa!

17:22.926 --> 17:24.280
Dad.

17:27.047 --> 17:28.685
Dad, we're sorry.

17:28.847 --> 17:29.916
Very sorry.

17:34.047 --> 17:36.515
He's back on the Cartwrights again.

17:37.287 --> 17:40.677
You know, someday we really should
ask him just who the hell they are.

17:42.807 --> 17:46.482
You know, Niles, one thing
just really bugs me.

17:46.687 --> 17:49.884
Houghton's gonna leave thinking we're
just a couple of inarticulate simpletons.

17:50.047 --> 17:52.481
What were those pithy comments
we made about his masterpiece?

17:52.687 --> 17:54.962
- "It was great."
BOTH: "Wow."

17:55.127 --> 17:58.324
<i>Yes, we'll go down in history with the
same boob who first read Hamlet,</i>

17:58.487 --> 18:02.321
then told Shakespeare, "My goodness,
what a parchment-turner!"

18:03.367 --> 18:05.597
Well, it's not too late.
He hasn't left yet.

18:06.287 --> 18:08.755
Yes, yes, we could still say
something to show him

18:08.927 --> 18:11.487
that we appreciated the
full complexity of his work.

18:13.807 --> 18:16.275
Mr Houghton, you know,
there is one further thing

18:16.447 --> 18:18.517
- I'd like to add about your book.
- Yeah.

18:18.727 --> 18:21.287
Well, it's the way you modulated
into the second-person narrative

18:21.447 --> 18:25.122
during the flashback scene. Frankly,
beggars anything Faulkner attempted.

18:25.327 --> 18:27.158
Really? That's very flattering.

18:27.847 --> 18:29.917
Oh, wait, I have one too.

18:30.607 --> 18:32.199
The way you so skilfully mirrored

18:32.367 --> 18:34.483
<i>the structure of Dante's
Divine Comedy was inspired.</i>

18:34.847 --> 18:35.836
Really?

18:36.007 --> 18:37.838
FRASIER:
Yes, from the inferno of the bordello...

18:38.007 --> 18:40.521
NILES: Which, we noticed,
had exactly nine rooms.

18:40.727 --> 18:43.400
- To the purgatory
of the assembly line,

18:43.567 --> 18:46.764
and finally to the paradise
of the farm.

18:47.647 --> 18:49.000
You both saw that?

18:49.167 --> 18:50.725
Oh, it practically jumped
off the page.

18:50.887 --> 18:53.196
Well, that's very perceptive of you.

18:53.407 --> 18:55.682
Well, thank you.
I guess it's our turn to be flattered.

18:55.887 --> 18:57.923
You're absolutely right.

18:58.247 --> 19:00.681
This whole book is crap.

19:00.887 --> 19:01.876
Beg your pardon?

19:02.087 --> 19:03.406
How could I be so blind?

19:03.567 --> 19:06.604
I lifted the entire structure
from Dante!

19:07.087 --> 19:09.840
- You mean you weren't going for that?
- Of course not!

19:10.047 --> 19:12.038
This confirms my worst fear.

19:12.247 --> 19:14.477
I have nothing original left to say.

19:14.687 --> 19:16.006
I'm an empty shell.

19:16.207 --> 19:18.243
I was a fool to think I had
a second book in me!

19:18.407 --> 19:21.046
"The winters were harsh
on the farm."

19:21.247 --> 19:24.398
Well, here's something
to warm them up!

19:24.567 --> 19:26.159
MARTIN:
What's going on here?

19:26.327 --> 19:27.316
You're both right.

19:27.527 --> 19:29.643
I'm a talentless hack
who got lucky once.

19:29.847 --> 19:32.042
- We didn't say that!
- You're not listening to them?

19:32.247 --> 19:34.807
- Look at this trash! It won't burn!
- It's a fireplace, you see.

19:34.967 --> 19:37.845
- It's not well ventilated.
- This doesn't belong in a fireplace.

19:38.407 --> 19:42.036
It belongs in the gutter,
with the rest of society's garbage!

19:42.207 --> 19:44.357
FRASIER: Wait. No, no...
MARTIN: Ted, don't do that!

19:44.527 --> 19:47.121
- Ted, no! Don't do it!
NILES: No, Mr Houghton...

19:53.287 --> 19:54.925
I want to thank you two.

19:55.247 --> 19:58.557
If I had published that book, my
reputation would have been destroyed.

19:58.727 --> 20:02.356
At least now I'm left
with a shred of dignity.

20:04.967 --> 20:06.286
No.

20:06.847 --> 20:08.246
MARTIN:
Happy?

20:08.407 --> 20:10.398
Hey, Ted, wait up!

20:18.367 --> 20:21.439
Well, we've destroyed a man's life.

20:22.007 --> 20:26.205
Not to mention depriving
future generations of a work of art.

20:26.367 --> 20:28.642
Yes, well, on the other hand,
had he actually published it,

20:28.807 --> 20:32.800
the critics surely would've noticed
that Dante parallel.

20:33.527 --> 20:35.802
If he felt bad now, imagine how
he would've felt reading it

20:35.967 --> 20:38.435
<i>- in The New York Review of Books.
- Oh, God, yes.</i>

20:38.647 --> 20:41.241
Given his fragile ego, my God,
he would've been devastated.

20:41.407 --> 20:43.159
Who knows what
he might have done.

20:44.727 --> 20:46.206
Do you know, Niles,

20:46.687 --> 20:48.837
we saved that man's life.

20:49.887 --> 20:52.321
Yes, I think you're right.

20:53.367 --> 20:56.086
- On the other hand...
- Don't go there.

20:58.887 --> 21:01.720
See, that's why
you're the older brother.

